## Security Features

### Native VLAN 99

The native VLAN was moved from the default **VLAN 1** to **VLAN 99**.  
This helps protect against **VLAN hopping attacks**, especially the **double-tagging exploit**.

In a double-tagging attack, an attacker on VLAN 1 can craft frames with two VLAN tags.  
The first tag is removed by the switch, allowing the second tag to reach another VLAN.

By placing the native VLAN on **VLAN 99** and not allowing user devices on it, this attack vector is removed.  
VLAN 99 is used only for **network device management**.



### SSH Instead of Telnet

**Telnet sends all traffic in plain text**, including usernames and passwords.  
Anyone capturing packets on the network could read these credentials.

**SSH version 2 encrypts the session** using RSA keys.  
This prevents attackers from capturing login credentials with packet sniffing tools.


### Unused Port Shutdown

All unused switch ports are **administratively shut down** and assigned to **VLAN 99**.

This prevents unauthorized physical access.  
If someone plugs into an unused port, they are placed on the management VLAN.

Since VLAN 99 has **no DHCP server and no default gateway**, the device cannot access the network.



### Port Security

**Sticky MAC learning** allows a switch port to learn the first MAC address it sees.  
That address becomes permanently associated with the port.

If another device connects, the switch detects a violation.  
The port enters **restrict mode** and logs the event.

This helps prevent unauthorized devices from connecting to the network.
